It seems like it would be worthwhile to safeguard ``getLastModifeidJobTime`` so that it can't concat 'Z' onto ``undefined`` again, regardless of how it's used.  Instead of ``job.last_modified + 'Z'``  it would be better to have some sane default in case we can't get ``job.last_modified``.  Perhaps::

    last_modified = job.last_modified || "1995-12-01T00:00:00"  // arbitrary, but guaranteed to not be the max
    return new Date(last_modified + 'Z')

@MrChrisJohnson not sure if I understand the O(k) algo you're describing

@a1k0n yes as i mentioned the reason you use different trees is to make sure you don't consistently separate the same two close points

but so far annoy has erred too much on the side of uncorrelated trees and too little on using the  distribution of the points. i think you could probably go a little further leveraging the distribution of the points

i'll prob just keep the 2-point solution for now. should be enough

```python
email  = account_info.get('user', {}).get('email')
if email:
    return User.query.filter_by(email=email).one_or_none()
